a mock up for a property-like api for event handler decorators

```python
class A(HasTraits):
    i = Int()

    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
        """The constructor for the class
        
        More details about the constructor"""
        pass

    # kwargs can be passed
    @j.observer(type='change')
    def h(self, change):
        print('i changed')

    # the generalized api
    @j.decorate(ValidateHandler)
    def g(self, commit):
        return commit['value']/2

    # streamlined api
    @j.default
    def f(self):
        return 1
```

The reason this isn't particularly clean to implement under the hood is because the decorator is run prior to when the trait has received its `name` attribute. Thus, capturing the name and passing it on to the handlers requires some extra logic using `class_init`.

I've seen people with this issue a couple times, most recently: https://github.com/venmo/business-rules/issues/16

This PR will allow variable decorators to be used with or without params/parens, like so:

```python
@string_rule_variable(label="My variable!")
def my_var(self):
    return "foo"

### OR

@string_rule_variable
def my_var(self):
    return "foo"
```

